{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559447/1945122701/0438.xml":{"full_text":"THE MARION PROGRESS\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY BY THE\nMcdowell publishing co.\nMARION, N. C.\nTELEPHONE 64\nS. E. WHITTEN, Editor and Proprietor\nEntered at the Postoffice at Marion, N. C.,\nas second class matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE:\nOne Year $1.50\nStrictly in Advance.\nj Carolina\nrmss association!\nAS WE APPROACH 1946\nAs the people of Marion face the beginning j\nof the year 1946 they should be thankful that\nthe nation has concluded its wars with far less\nloss of American lives than looked probable\nas the year 1945 began.\nThe rapid demobilization of our armed\nforces has enabled many service men to return\nto their families and the process continues to\npromise an early return of our service men to\ncivilian life. This poses serious problems for\nthe veterans and for the communities to which\nthey return and we hope that the end of 1946\n\u25a0will reveal that adequate attention has been\npaid to this matter.\nLast year, at this time, the Germans were in\nthe midst of their great drive into Belgium,\nwith many Americans suffering misgivings as\nto' what might be ahead. Luckily, the enemy\noffensive was halted and the campaign against\nthe Nazis pushed to a conclusion that came\nearlier and easier than appeared possible.\nThe war with Japan, fought largely by\nnaval forces, reached its climax with the cap\nture of Okinawa and the blasting of Japanese\ncities by planes and warships. The great ad\nvances scored by naval and aerial operations\nmade unnecessary the invasion that was being\nrapidly prepared for the home islands of Japan\nand saved the lives of thousands of our fighting\nmen.\nOn the home front the inconveniences of the\nwar period are rapidly disappearing, with ra\ntioning a thing of the past for the most part.\nThe threat of inflation continues to menace\nthe fundamental prosperity of the future and\nit will have to be met during the coming twelve\nmonths. Certain essential controls must be\nmaintained or the economic history, of 1946\nwill prove to be the forerunner of a dismal\nplunge into a depression of great magnitude.\nOn the hopeful side is the organization of\nthe United Nations, which promises that peace\nis possible if the nations sincerely and unsel\nfishly cooperate. The United States has re\nversed its decision following the last World i\nWar and is wholeheartedly supporting the in\nternational association of nations which may,\nin time, develop into something like the gov\nernment of the United States, but including\nnations instead of colonies.\nWhile we have refered to national and in\nternational issues the great question of the\nyear, about to begin, is what it holds in store\nfor the individuals who read this article. There\nis no certain answer because it all depends\nupon what the individual does for himself or\nherself. We hope that our readers will make\n1946 a banner year in their lives but the job\nis strictly up to them.\nThe Progress promises to give the same ser\nvice it has attempted to render the pople of\nMcDowell county in the past. We hope that,\nsome of the factors that have prevented the!\ndevelopment of our plans will disappear and!\nthat we will be able to print more news and\npublish a better newspaper than ever before, j\nIn conclusion, we hope that every reader j\nwill enjoy a happy and prosperous year and j\nthat, in retrospective view, we will be able i\nto consider 1946 a banner year. Let's go!\nDEPRESSION, THEN BOOM\nWhile there is no way of ascertaining the\ncorrectness of the prediction made by econ\nomists, and the record shows that they are;\nwrong about as often as anybody else, the j\npublic is usually interested in what a so-called\nexpert thinks about future trends.\nThis leads to the views of General Leonard\nC. Ayers, Cleveland banker, who, in a recent\naddress, declared that business is entering a\nprimary post-war depression, evidenced by in\ncreasing unemployment, declining production\nand falling national incomes, but added that\nthis is to be expected after a great war and\ncoincides with the transition into peacetime\neconomy.\nThe economist does not consider the con\ndition alarming and predicts that the national\nincome will begin to rise as early as the mid\ndle of 1946. While reconversion may be re\ntarded and production curtailed by labor\n'strikes and price controls, the Cleveland man\nsees a boom of great intensity and of probably\nconsiderable duration in the nation.\nI\nHe points out that the people have \"short\nages of everything except money,\" that many\ndebts have been paid, that savings have ac\ncumulated and that the public now has about\nfour times as much actual and potential pur\nchasing power as it possessed in 1929.\nPHYSICAL EDUCATION NEEDED\nA publication of the National Education As-j\nsociation tells us that \"adequate school health!\nprograms are imperative\" which is about what|\nwe have tried to tell our readers for some\nyears.\nOne out of every three men, called into ser\nvice after Pearl Harbor, was unfit for duty.\nThis applies to those between the ages of 18\n37 but even among the 18-19 group the rejec\ntions were one out of four.\nIn the 18-19 ages rejections among the!\nwhites were 23.8 per cent and among Negroes j\n45.5 per cent. For farm youth the rejections\nwere 41 per cent compared to 25 per cent for!\nall occupational groups.\nThis evidence of physical disability is not\nonly a challenge to th\u00a7 nation but a condem\nnation. Parents, schools, public health ser- j\nvice, doctors and lawmakers share the blame, j\nEvery individual is partly responsible insofar;\nas he, or she, did not do anything to remedy\nthe appalling lack of proper physical educa\ntion and development.\nThere are some signs of physical education\nin McDowell county but the truth of the mat\nter is that what has been attempted is woefully\ninadequate. Even the programs of our largest\nschools is but a feeble start upon the great's\ntask of insuring proper physical growth for\nboys and girls.\nAuthorities suggest that adequate school j\nprograms are imperative. They are right in j\nthis suggestion, even if the program costs I\nmoney. School years are critical for physical!\ngrowth and most students need, more than j\never, a sensible routine of health, physical!\neducation and proper recreation.\nI\nI\nj\nIf you haven't given enough money to chari\ntable causes you still have time to make the i\ngift, and earn a deduction on your income tax j\nreturn. j\n1\n1\nThe Everyday\nCounselor\n\u2014BY\u2014\nRev. Herbert Spaugh,\nD. D.\nA troubled reader is coming to the end of\n1945 worried, confused, and burdened with a\ndeep sense of sin. She admits that she has!\ncome to the \"what's the use?\" stage. There!\nare probably many others who feel as she. i\nMore would feel the same way if they took I\ntime to sit down and reflect over the sins of j\nthe past year. All of us have a record which\nbrings some unhappy recollections. Christmas\njust passed has an answer for that, because\nChristmas commemorates the- \"unspeakable\nGift*' of God\u2014His Son who came into the world\nto save sinners. Because God gave mankind j\nthe greatest gift at Christmas-time, we give j\ngifts to one another.\nIn the Moravian Christmas Candle Service,\nheld on Christmas Eve, small lighted wax ta\npers are distributed to all members of the con\ngregation. Wax, a product of \"the flesh\" is,\nused to indicate the humanity of Christ. The 1\nlighted wick symbolizes His divinity. Wrap\nped around the candle is a red band as a re\nminder of the atonement of Christ on the cross\nfor the sins of mankind.\nIn the message of Christmas there is hope j\nfor the sinner. Jesus said. \"Him that cometh\nto me, I v/ill in no wise cast out.\" During His!\nlifetime here on earth there was no sinner, no j\nmatter how low he had stooped, who was not\nreceived by the Saviour when he came to Him\nin true repentence. Mary Magdalene Was one,\nout of whom it was written that He had to\n\"cast seven devils\". Seven is the complete\nnumber in the Bible, in this case indicating the\ncompleteness of her sin. She was completely\nforgiven and honored in being the first to wel\ncome the Risen Saviour.\nj Simon Peter, who became One of the greatest\njleaders of the Christian Church, sunk so low\nj in sin as to deny his Lord at the hoUr when\nhe was needed most.\nJesus has taught that which the church has\ncontinued to teach, that there is complete for\ngiveness for the sinner who comes to his Lord\ni in true repentence. The Holy Communion is\na reminder of the forgiveness which the Christ\nian believer, who has sinned, may receive Upon\n!true confession.\nForgiveness is not earned; it is a gift of God.\nLike a parent who forgives an erring child who\ncomes seeking forgiveness, God grants it to His\nerring children through Jesus Christ.\nHaving received the gift in true faith, guilt\nis washed away, and a new page is before us.\nWe should put the thought and worry of the\nforgiven sins behind us, and write on that new\npage.\nHAPPY NEW YEAR\nWe sincerely thank you for your patronage of the\npast and hope we can be of further service in 1946.\nWe wish you all the best of health, success and hap\npiness throughout the coming year.\nMarion Machine Co.\nGREETINGS\nThe beginning of the New Year is a time to ex\npress our appreciation for the loyal patronage in the\nyear just ended and to express the hope that our\nrelations in the year to come may be still more\npleasant and successful.\nMarion Ice Coal Co.\nServing This Community for Over 25 Years","height":"31328","width":"21448"}}
